## Testing Standards

### Unit Testing

- Tests live alongside the code they test in `*_test.go` files.
- Test file naming: `<source_file>_test.go` (e.g., `watermark_test.go`).
- Use the standard `testing` package; no external test frameworks.
- Every test function must start with `Test` followed by a descriptive name in PascalCase.

```go
func TestReadEXIF_MissingFile(t *testing.T) { ... }
func TestAddWatermark_NoEXIFData(t *testing.T) { ... }
func TestResizeForWhatsApp_LargeImage(t *testing.T) { ... }
```

### Table-Driven Tests

Prefer table-driven tests for functions with multiple input/output scenarios:

```go
func TestOutputPath(t *testing.T) {
    cases := []struct {
        name      string
        inputPath string
        outDir    string
        want      string
    }{
        {"jpg in subdir", "photos/img.jpg", "out", "out/img.jpg"},
        {"arw file",      "raw/shot.arw",  "out", "out/shot.jpg"},
        {"png file",      "img.png",       ".",   "./img.jpg"},
    }
    for _, tc := range cases {
        t.Run(tc.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            got := OutputPath(tc.inputPath, tc.outDir)
            if got != tc.want {
                t.Errorf("got %q, want %q", got, tc.want)
            }
        })
    }
}
```

### Test Coverage Requirements

| Package | Minimum coverage |
|---------|-----------------|
| `lib/`  | 80% statements  |
| `cli/`  | 60% statements  |
| `gui/`  | Best-effort (Fyne widgets require a display; mock the processor boundary) |

Run coverage locally:
```bash
go test ./lib/ -coverprofile=coverage.out && go tool cover -html=coverage.out
```

### Mocking and Fakes

- `lib/` has no external side effects beyond the filesystem and optional external tools (`dcraw`, ImageMagick).
- For filesystem-dependent tests, use `t.TempDir()` to create isolated directories.
- For functions that shell out (`exec.Command`), inject a `lookPath` function or use build tags to swap in a fake.
- Do not mock the filesystem with an abstraction layer — the overhead is not justified for this project size.

